</ul>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p><b>Listed buildings</b><sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12"><span>[</span>12<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<ul>
<li>Grade II*&#160;: Chalford Place, St John the Baptist, St Mary's House, Wing Cottage</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>Grade II&#160;: Baptist Chapel, Church of St Michael and All Angels, Christ Church, France Congregational Church and Hall</li>
</ul>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Modern_Chalford">Modern Chalford</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Chalford&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Modern Chalford">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>In February 2008, Chalford hit the headlines when a community plan to reintroduce donkeys as a way of carrying shopping up the steep, narrow hills became public.<sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13"><span>[</span>13<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14"><span>[</span>14<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15"><span>[</span>15<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>On 5 September 2009 Chalford Community Stores allowed customers to purchase shares in the business. The store, which has been running with the aid of a volunteer workforce since 2003, is now affiliated with the independent organisation Co-operatives UK, making the share issue possible.<sup id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-16"><span>[</span>16<span>]</span></a></sup> On 4&#160;March 2012 the store and the donkey were featured in an episode of <a href="/wiki/Countryfile" title="Countryfile">Countryfile</a>. The store currently resides within the local church but is due to return to the High Street in May 2014 in the former Seventh Day Adventist Hall. This was made possible by a second community share issue which raised in excess of £50,000 alongside a bank loan and various grants.</p>
<p>Chalford is home to the national literacy charity Readathon.<sup id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17"><span>[</span>17<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Residents">Residents</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Chalford&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Residents">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Notable residents include <a href="/wiki/James_Bradley" title="James Bradley">James Bradley</a>, the third <a href="/wiki/Astronomer_Royal" title="Astronomer Royal">Astronomer Royal</a>, who died in Chalford in 1762, and the 19th-century sculptor <a href="/wiki/John_Thomas_(sculptor)" title="John Thomas (sculptor)">John Thomas</a>. <a href="/wiki/Henry_Cooper" title="Henry Cooper">Henry Cooper</a> lived in the village as a child, after being evacuated here during the Second World War.<sup id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-18"><span>[</span>18<span>]</span></a></sup> The artist <a href="/wiki/Damien_Hirst" title="Damien Hirst">Damien Hirst</a> has a studio in the village. <a href="/wiki/Robin_Janvrin,_Baron_Janvrin" title="Robin Janvrin, Baron Janvrin">Lord Janvrin</a>, former Private Secretary to H.M. the Queen, maintains a house in the village and on his retirement was gazetted as Baron Janvrin of Chalford Hill, on 10&#160;October 2007. The Public Relations guru <a href="/wiki/Mark_Borkowski" title="Mark Borkowski">Mark Borkowski</a> lives at Oakridge.</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Brownshill">Brownshill</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Chalford&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Brownshill">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Brownshill is home to the Monastery of Our Lady and St Bernard which is home to a community of eight <a href="/wiki/Bernardine" title="Bernardine" class="mw-disambig">Bernardine</a> <a href="/wiki/Cistercian" title="Cistercian" class="mw-redirect">Cistercian</a> nuns. <sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19"><span>[</span>19<span>]</span></a></sup> There is a sister community at the Monastery of Our Lady of Hyning at <a href="/wiki/Warton" title="Warton" class="mw-disambig">Warton</a>, near <a href="/wiki/Carnforth" title="Carnforth">Carnforth</a>.</p>
<p><a href="/wiki/St_Mary_of_the_Angels_Church,_Brownshill" title="St Mary of the Angels Church, Brownshill">St Mary of the Angels</a> is a small Roman Catholic church built at Brownshill in the 1930s with funds from two former nurses, Bertha Kessler and Katherine Hudson. The architect was <a href="/wiki/W._D._Caroe" title="W. D. Caroe">W. D. Caroe</a>, with windows by <a href="/wiki/Douglas_Strachan" title="Douglas Strachan">Douglas Strachan</a>. <sup id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-20"><span>[</span>20<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="See_also">See also</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Chalford&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: See also">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="/wiki/Aston_Down" title="Aston Down">Aston Down</a> airfield across the Golden Valley from Chalford</li>
</ul>
